questions_prompt:
Please ensure the questions you ask cover the key functional, logical, architectural, implementation, debugging, optimization, review, and problem-solving areas from the competency scope for {name}, matched to {proficiency} proficiency ({yoe} years experience).

Focus the assessment content on these Scala topic areas and sub-skills, explicitly and directly:
- Expression-oriented problem solving, immutability by default, deciding when mutability is justified, call-by-value vs call-by-name tradeoffs, lazy evaluation implications, recursion and tail-recursive algorithm design.
- Pattern matching for business logic, including nested patterns, guards, custom extractors, and partial functions in data-processing or event-handling flows.
- Object-oriented design in Scala: classes, abstract classes, traits, objects, companion objects, encapsulation, modularity, inheritance vs composition vs delegation tradeoffs, self-types for component wiring, mixins, trait linearization, case classes, sealed hierarchies, and ADT-based domain modeling.
- Functional design: referential transparency where appropriate, side-effect discipline, higher-order functions, currying, partial application, immutable data modeling, persistent collections, and using ADTs to represent business states and invalid-state prevention.
- Generic API and type-driven design: type parameters, bounds, variance, designing generic interfaces safely, reasoning about type inference issues, higher-kinded abstractions, type class-based design, context-driven abstractions, and Tagless Final style where relevant to architecture.
- Advanced type modeling where it affects real design decisions: abstract type members vs type parameters, path-dependent or member types when used for module boundaries, type constraints and evidence-based restrictions, and practical use of Scala 3 concepts such as union/intersection types or opaque wrappers in migration-aware codebases.
- Collection and data structure choice: selecting appropriate immutable or mutable collections based on access/update patterns, reasoning about time/space tradeoffs, avoiding unnecessary intermediate collections, using lazy transformations or views when beneficial, and exposing safe immutable facades over mutable internals in performance-sensitive modules.
- Asynchronous and concurrent workflows using Future/Promise/ExecutionContext, for-comprehensions and combinators, selecting execution contexts based on CPU-bound vs IO-bound work, and debugging common production issues such as starvation, deadlocks, blocking misuse, race conditions, and timeout behavior.
- Actor/message-driven and stream-oriented design where relevant: actor hierarchies, supervision, backpressure, bounded mailboxes, throttling, stream topology design, failure handling, buffering, and integration with HTTP, persistence, queues, or Kafka-style pipelines.
- Effect-system-based design with Cats Effect, ZIO, or equivalent: modeling side effects explicitly, cancellation, resource lifecycles, fibers or structured concurrency primitives, and safe acquisition/release patterns.
- Error handling and resilience: using Option/Either/Try appropriately, distinguishing domain errors from unexpected failures, typed error models, error accumulation where useful, and pragmatic resilience choices in service code.
- Resource safety and lifecycle management for files, connections, threads, streams, and long-running services, including legacy and structured approaches.
- Web/API implementation concerns: REST endpoint design, routing/controller structure, middleware/filtering, separation of concerns, authentication/authorization integration, and service layering.
- Persistence and integration work: schema-to-type modeling, transaction boundaries, query/stream handling, retry semantics, connection-pool considerations, migration-aware persistence evolution, and integration with JSON/binary serialization, messaging systems, and external APIs.
- Distributed/data-processing scenarios where relevant: transformations, aggregations, streaming jobs, serialization concerns, memory/performance issues, and troubleshooting distributed Scala jobs.
- Performance and optimization: JVM-aware reasoning, allocation and boxing overhead, hot-path improvement, minimizing closure/intermediate collection overhead, safe use of mutable structures in critical sections, identifying inefficient pattern matching or runtime-heavy constructs, and interpreting runtime signals such as stack traces, thread dumps, or GC-related symptoms.
- Java interoperability and adaptation layers: wrapping Java libraries into idiomatic Scala APIs, null and exception boundaries, collection adaptation, and designing Scala components that integrate cleanly with Java-heavy systems.
- Service and application architecture: layered or hexagonal architecture, ports-and-adapters, algebraic interfaces, domain/application/infrastructure separation, rich type-safe domain models, and organization of large Scala codebases with enforceable module boundaries.
- Pattern selection and tradeoff analysis: OO vs FP decomposition, synchronous vs asynchronous APIs, direct-style vs effectful interfaces, type sophistication vs readability/team maintainability, and reasoned ecosystem/tooling choices based on constraints.
- Scala 2 to Scala 3 migration-aware reasoning: implications of givens/using, extension methods, enums, union/intersection types, opaque types, incompatibility handling, incremental migration strategy, and library/API evolution with backward-compatibility concerns.
- Code review and technical leadership behaviors grounded in code: reviewing for correctness, idiomatic design, performance, maintainability, anti-pattern detection, documentation clarity, and improvement guidance for less experienced developers.
- Practical use of implicits/givens, extension-based APIs, derivation-backed libraries, and reflection-backed utilities only where they materially affect implementation, design, maintainability, or runtime tradeoffs.

Do not ask questions about testing frameworks, test setup, tool installation, build-tool setup steps, language trivia, syntax recall, or pure semantic definitions. Prefer realistic tasks where the candidate must solve, fix, build, review, debug, optimize, or evolve a real Scala work item.

This is a basic proficiency, so the tasks need to match one year of experience only. Somebody with one year of experience does not have extensive production experience and their concepts are usually shaky, so the complexity of the task needs to be basic only. Let the candidate be able to finish this within 15 minutes.

Prefer scenarios that assess:
- understanding of requirements and constraints;
- reasoning through ambiguous or incomplete real-world situations;
- quality of technical decisions and tradeoff analysis;
- ability to identify likely root causes, risks, failure modes, and edge cases;
- proposing or implementing pragmatic, maintainable solutions;
- reviewing and improving existing code, design, or architecture;
- debugging issues in business logic, concurrency, data flow, integration boundaries, performance, or reliability;
- making sound simplifications appropriate to the stated proficiency and time limit.

Design prompts so candidates work on realistic Scala tasks such as:
- fixing flawed business logic in a sealed-trait/ADT-based workflow;
- reviewing an API or module design and suggesting safer type or error models;
- debugging a Future/effect/concurrency issue causing starvation, timeout, or race symptoms;
- improving a collection-heavy transformation pipeline with better data-structure or allocation choices;
- refactoring imperative or mutation-heavy code into a safer, more maintainable Scala design where appropriate;
- identifying risks in actor, stream, persistence, or integration code and proposing targeted improvements;
- evaluating architectural choices for service boundaries, layering, effect style, or migration strategy;
- adapting Java-facing or legacy Scala 2 code into a cleaner, safer Scala interface.

The goal is to evaluate applied competence, practical problem-solving, implementation and review ability, sound technical judgment, and the candidate's ability to deliver realistic solutions within the expected time constraints for their proficiency level.
